iberal paradox, problems in the measurement of freedom and choice and the differences between instrumental and intrinsic accounts of the value of freedom and related concepts. The wide-ranging material will provide an excellent text for students at all levels. It is appropriate reading for a host of courses in the fields of political science, political sociology and political theory at both undergraduate and graduate level. Whilst addressing some philosophically difficult and advanced subjects, the accessible writing makes the subject-matter comprehensible for all levels of students.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aLibertyxPolitical aspects. 0aPower (Social sciences). 4aPolitical Studies 2019. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh  aChoice.  aDowding.  aFreedom.  aLiberal paradox.  aLiberty.  aLuck.  aPower.  aResponsibility.  aRights.  aSystematic luck.1 aDowding, Keith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2016 eBook-Packagez978311128282440uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152610455740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526104557423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526104557/original  a978-3-11-128282-4  Manchester University Press 2016 eBook-Packageb2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles